<div id="review_159226920" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/159226920" />
    <a title="Diane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4190284-diane"><img alt="Diane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380393403p2/4190284.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/159226920?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane" href="/user/show/4190284-diane">Diane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4190284-diane?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer159226920" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9105539189437653669">My rule is this: give a book at least 50 pages to engage and keep my interest. I read about 65 pages and gave up. I just didn&apos;t care about any of the characters.<br/><br/>I wanted to like this book. I love the Art Deco movement. I think Tiffany mosaics are amazing. I am interested in the time period. But Clara was just not an interesting protagonist. I couldn&apos;t keep motivated to continue reading this book. <br/><br/>Clara, a former Tiffany employee, gets her job back after her husband&apos;s death. (Tiffany has a rule a</span>
  <span id="freeText9105539189437653669" style="display:none">My rule is this: give a book at least 50 pages to engage and keep my interest. I read about 65 pages and gave up. I just didn't care about any of the characters.<br /><br />I wanted to like this book. I love the Art Deco movement. I think Tiffany mosaics are amazing. I am interested in the time period. But Clara was just not an interesting protagonist. I couldn't keep motivated to continue reading this book. <br /><br />Clara, a former Tiffany employee, gets her job back after her husband's death. (Tiffany has a rule against employing married women.) She is a master at color and implements Tiffany's painted renderings into mosaic glass. She manages a bunch of other women artists. Okay. <br /><br />Her homelife is that she lives in a boarding house, filled with interesting people. All of them MORE interesting than she is. She meets a dreamy man...a humanitarian, a go-getter, an international traveler...and she gives up love for career. I didn't actually believe the romance, since it wasn't actually romantic. I didn't understand her adoration of Mr. Tiffany; he was a bit of a jerk. <br /><br />The bits about the way the art was created was interesting, but ham-handedly interjected into the story. I kept feeling as though all Ms. Vreeland's research was being spoon-fed to me. It wasn't very artfully inserted into the story, but jammed in. <br /><br />I think I will read Clara's wikipedia article instead of finishing the book, and maybe look online for images of the Tiffany mosaics. I have already seen an incredible one in Cleveland (in a cemetary at that!) <br /><br />As for the book, it was a disappointment after The Girl in Hyacinth Blue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9105539189437653669" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


